structured.title: Critique Of Prophetic Use Of Social Media Data
structured.overview: The speakers, led primarily by one main commentator, analyze and criticize alleged prophetic practices of a figure named Sean (often referred to as Sean Bolz). They focus on how he appears to rely on publicly available social media information and usernames instead of genuine supernatural insight. Examples include misreading or guessing usernames (like "TerryBishop911" and "BabsElrick"), confusion over whether names are real or just handles, and repeatedly pulling very specific biographical details from people‚Äôs Facebook pages and personal testimony videos. A friend of the commentator, Steven Kozar, is referenced and quoted as he systematically shows how Sean‚Äôs words to an individual named Dennis at the Azusa Now event match Dennis‚Äô existing online testimony and Facebook profile (Ukrainian background, move to Washington, difficult youth, bullying, drugs, juvenile detention, ministry name ‚ÄúAwakening Generation,‚Äù current location). The argument is that Sean combines highly specific past and present details that are easy to data-mine with vague, non-specific future prophecies, forming a pattern the commentator calls manipulative, abusive, and fraudulent, especially when people like Dennis may base life decisions and fundraising appeals on these ‚Äúwords.‚Äù

apps_results.content:
## Username-based ‚Äúprophecies‚Äù  
- Repeated ‚Äúwords‚Äù given from Facebook usernames, not real names  
- Examples: ‚ÄúBearBishop911,‚Äù ‚ÄúBabsElrick‚Äù treated as God-given details  
- Presenter calls username focus itself suspicious and pattern-based  

## Misreading and conflating names  
- Prophet mispronounces and merges separate names (e.g., Babs + Elrick)  
- Assumes screen handles are actual legal names of people  
- Used as evidence he‚Äôs reading online, not hearing from God  

## Steven Kozar‚Äôs investigative analysis  
- Kozar compares prophecies to public social media data  
- Shows Sean‚Äôs detailed past/present info fully online beforehand  
- Notes future ‚Äúprophecies‚Äù stay vague, non-specific, low-risk  

## Case study: Dennis  
- Dennis‚Äô Ukrainian background, move to Washington, arrests all online  
- Sean repeats these facts as prophecy at Azusa Now 2016  
- Dennis likely checked in/used hashtags, making him easy to find  

## Emotional and financial impact on Dennis  
- Word confirms Dennis‚Äô ‚Äúlife mission,‚Äù increasing his commitment  
- Presenter says Dennis may have fundraised based on this prophecy  
- Urges Dennis to stop using Sean‚Äôs word as fundraising basis  

## Pattern and conclusion about Sean  
- Pattern: specific public facts + vague future predictions  
- Data-mining explanation fits repeated cases across multiple people  
- Presenter concludes ‚Äúno reasonable doubt‚Äù Sean is faking  

## Next steps  
- Presenter plans more evidence from ex-staff and associates  
- Intends to tell the ‚Äúwhole story‚Äù about Sean‚Äôs methods  
- Suggests victims reassess decisions made from these prophecies
